        <marc:subfield code="a">ger: Die vorliegende Arbeit ist in zwei Teilen dargestellt:1.Die Technik im Sinne der griechischen Philosophie der Antike. Der Begriff τέχνη (téchnè) im technikphilosophischen Sinne von Sokrates, Platon und Aristoteles wird erörtert. Danach folgt die neue Bedeutung dieses Begriffes in der modernen Philosophie der Technik bei Martin Heidegger. Die Technikphilosophie wird auch aus verschieden Perspektiven von einigen Philosophen ausgelegt (Heidegger, Beck, Gehlen, Habermas, Jonas, Ullrich usw.). Dieser Teil beantwortet zwei Fragen:•Wie wurde der Begriff τέχνη in der griechischen Philosophie der Antike ausgelegt?•Wie hat sich die Definition der τέχνη im 20. und 21. Jahrhundert geändert?2.Der zweite Teil erörtert die Technikphilosophie des 20. und 21. Jahrhunderts am Beispiel der Risiken und Gefahren der Massenvernichtungstechnologie von Atomkraftwerken und Atombomben. Die technisch-moralische und -ethische Verantwortung werden ebenfalls diskutiert.Dieser Teil wird durch die Entstehung des Atoms als Begriff im naturphilosophischen Sinne der griechischen Antike bei Leukippos (Deutsch: Leukipp) und Demokritos (Demokrit) im 5./4. Jahrhundert v. C. eingeführt. Diese zwei Philosophen prägten zuerst den Begriff des ἄτομος (des Atoms oder des Unteilbaren) und dementsprechend die materialistisch-atomistische Lehre. Ihrer Meinung nach: Die Wirklichkeit ist eine Erscheinung der Wahrnehmung der menschlichen Sinnesorgane (Sensualismus). Die Wirklichkeit ist eine Eigenschaft der vielfaltigen Zustände, Umfang, Gewicht, Festigkeit, Ausdehnung Menge, Masse, Form, Stärke, Ausbreitung und Gebilde der Atome, sowie ihre Anziehungs- und Abstoßungskräfte. Die Seele („Urfeuer“) besteht aus feinst kleinsten Atomen.</marc:subfield>
    </marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <marc:subfield code="a">eng: The present work is presented in two parts:1. The technique in the sense of Greek philosophy of antiquity. The term τέχνη (téchnè) in the technico-philosophical sense of Socrates, Plato and Aristotle is discussed. This is followed by the new meaning of this term in the modern philosophy of technology by Martin Heidegger.The philosophy of technology is also interpreted from different perspectives by some philosophers (Heidegger, Beck, Gehlen, Habermas, Jonas, Ullrich, etc.). This part answers two questions:• How was the concept τέχνη interpreted in the Greek philosophy of antiquity?• How has the definition of τέχνη changed in the 20th and 21st centuries?2. The second part discusses the engineering philosophy of the 20th and 21st centuries by examining the risks and dangers of the mass destruction technology of nuclear power plants and atomic bombs. The technical-moral and ethical responsibilities are also discussed.This part is explained by the origin of the atom as a concept in the natural-philosophical sense of Greek antiquity in Leukippos (German: Leukipp) and Democritus (Democritus) in the 5th and 4th centuries. Century v. C. introduced. These two philosophers first shaped the concept of ἄτομος (the atom or the indivisible) and accordingly the materialistic-atomistic doctrine. In your opinion: Reality is a phenomenon of the perception of the human organs of sense (sensualism). Reality is a property of the diverse states, extent, weight, strength, expansion, mass, shape, strength, propagation and structure of the atoms, as well as their attracting and repelling forces. The soul (&quot;primal fire&quot;) consists of very finest atoms.I would like to point out that the present work was developed from seminars I had written at various universities in Austria.CONTENTS OF PRESENT WORKChapter I. gives an overview of the ancient technique (τέχνη).The philosophy of technology is presented in chapter II from different perspectives of philosophers, natural scientists and sociologists (Heidegger, Beck, Gehlen, Habermas, Jonas, Ullrich, Dessauer, etc.).In chapter III. The technology is viewed critically: Martin Heidegger addressed the &quot;question of technology&quot; in the light of modern technology, influenced by the mass destruction of the atomic bombs and the technical and moral responsibility (as exemplified by Hiroshima and Nagasaki) from the nuclear power plants Respectively. The Chernobyl catastrophe is also analyzed within the framework of morality, ethics and responsibility.REQUIREMENTS, METHODOLOGY AND LITERATURE• What was the meaning of the term τέχνη (téchnè) in Socrates, Plato and Aristotle?• How did the τέχνη develop philosophically from the 18th century, the beginning of the industrial revolution?• How did Martin Heidegger deal with the philosophy of technology in the second half of the 20th century, &quot;in the age of mass destruction technology&quot;, such as the nuclear bombs developed as a by-product from the development of nuclear reactor reactors?• What consequences can be expected from the technology philosophy of Martin Heidegger?• Where are the limits of moral chance and responsibility at risk and danger of technology, as exemplified by Chernobyl, Hiroshima and Nagasaki?• Who is / are to blame for such &quot;random&quot; disasters, where innocent people should die?• Modern technology is becoming increasingly dangerous. Where is &quot;the danger&quot; and who is &quot;the saving&quot;? (Heidegger, 1953, 36)• &quot;What is technology?&quot; (Heidegger 1953, 5)This work attempts to answer these questions. The working method is based on literature investigations and discussion of philosophical questions.</marc:subfield>
